It's late.

1262
02:05:32,543 --> 02:05:36,305
All right, motions, orders, and resolutions.

1263
02:05:36,325 --> 02:05:59,856
17-505, offered by Vice President Mox, being resolved that the city administration perform a complete audit on the condition of our roads and provide the council with a complete assessment, including curbing, sidewalk, catch basin, sewer covers, and handicapped rents, being further resolved that the city prioritize the list according to the road and infrastructure condition.

1264
02:06:00,296 --> 02:06:01,437
Vice President Mox.

1265
02:06:02,557 --> 02:06:18,542
Thank you Mr. President and you know this has been an issue that's been on the council agenda probably for the last several years and it's an issue that I believe is one of the top three issues

1266
02:06:19,005 --> 02:06:21,425
that I feel as a member of the city council.

1267
02:06:21,865 --> 02:06:39,088
And it's been, it's been very consistent over the years, the poor condition of our roads and the fact that, uh, in my opinion, uh, the city really doesn't have a game plan on, uh, repairing the roads or replacing our roads.

1268
02:06:39,829 --> 02:06:45,990
And I did a little homework and went into, uh, the engineering department last week.

1269
02:06:46,330 --> 02:06:47,830
I went into the finance department.

1270
02:06:48,263 --> 02:06:52,947
to get a little information on really what we're doing as a community on our streets.

1271
02:06:53,788 --> 02:06:56,270
And I found it pretty interesting, Mr. President.

1272
02:06:56,970 --> 02:07:04,036
First of all, a lion's share of the money we receive every year to do road work comes from the state.

1273
02:07:04,837 --> 02:07:06,498
It comes from Chapter 90 money.

1274
02:07:07,419 --> 02:07:15,966
And many people at home may not know, but Chapter 90 money is a program that entitles municipalities to 100% reimbursement

1275
02:07:17,635 --> 02:07:22,244
of documented expenditures on approved projects for maintaining

1276
02:07:22,680 --> 02:07:28,525
repairing, improving and constructing town and county ways and bridges.

1277
02:07:29,326 --> 02:07:38,274
So we get roughly $900,000 a year through this chapter 90 money earmarked to improvement of our roads.

1278
02:07:39,075 --> 02:07:49,164
We also get, and it fluctuates year to year, we get money from the office of community development for road repair and that could vary from

1279
02:07:50,193 --> 02:07:52,494
150,000 to 300,000 a year.

1280
02:07:53,034 --> 02:08:07,577
So you're looking at roughly $1.1 million a year allocation to improve our roads from the state and actually OCD, which comes from, I believe, the federal government.

1281
02:08:08,458 --> 02:08:11,538
The allocation amount is based on three different factors.

1282
02:08:12,539 --> 02:08:15,259
How many road miles do you have in your community?

1283
02:08:15,799 --> 02:08:17,320
That weighs in at a 58%

1284
02:08:20,430 --> 02:08:25,936
So it's very important how many road miles you have in your community when they allocate this money through Chapter 90.

1285
02:08:26,516 --> 02:08:31,642
Population is 20.83% of the formula.

1286
02:08:32,102 --> 02:08:35,666
So your population size weighs in on how much money you get back.

1287
02:08:36,857 --> 02:08:38,858
the employment within the community.

1288
02:08:38,878 --> 02:08:41,518
Do you have high or low employment in the community?

1289
02:08:41,978 --> 02:08:43,139
That weighs in also at 20.83%.

1290
02:08:45,299 --> 02:08:53,641
So all those three factors, uh, will, uh, be what determines how the state allocates this chapter 90 money.

1291
02:08:54,482 --> 02:08:55,202
And, uh, in 2018,

1292
02:08:57,146 --> 02:09:01,887
The governor is allocating $200 million for the entire state.

1293
02:09:02,768 --> 02:09:10,170
Our allocation for the city of Medford, based on the three factors, we have 91 miles of road in our community.

1294
02:09:10,690 --> 02:09:12,750
Our population is roughly 56,173.

1295
02:09:16,210 --> 02:09:21,035
And our employment is about 18,474 in the community.

1296
02:09:21,536 --> 02:09:26,581
So based on those numbers, where we average with all the other communities, we're receiving 944,095.

1297
02:09:31,558 --> 02:09:32,118
in dollars.

1298
02:09:32,779 --> 02:09:34,659
Last year, we received $951,000.

1299
02:09:35,300 --> 02:09:39,401
The prior year, FY16, $950,000.

1300
02:09:39,721 --> 02:09:43,083
So it's been very consistent over the years.

1301
02:09:43,103 --> 02:09:51,326
And we move forward, and we spend the money, and then we get reimbursed by the state through this Chapter 90 money.

1302
02:09:52,146 --> 02:09:54,227
The unfortunate thing about it, Mr. President,

1303
02:09:55,051 --> 02:09:57,393
is that's all we're putting towards the roads.

1304
02:09:57,873 --> 02:10:03,677
Whatever we get through Chapter 90, which is great, 100% reimbursement, sign me up every year.

1305
02:10:04,837 --> 02:10:06,058
But there's a problem with that.

1306
02:10:06,619 --> 02:10:09,080
It's great that we get it, but it's not enough.

1307
02:10:09,801 --> 02:10:11,242
And we've been doing this for years.

1308
02:10:12,022 --> 02:10:15,284
And we know that our roads have not improved over the years.

1309
02:10:15,825 --> 02:10:21,208
So it's clear to me, when you look at these figures, that we're never gonna get ahead of the game.

1310
02:10:21,228 --> 02:10:24,010
We're always gonna be chasing our tail on the roads.

1311
02:10:25,647 --> 02:10:30,330
We have 730 streets in the city of Method.

1312
02:10:30,350 --> 02:10:32,211
40% of them are private ways.

1313
02:10:32,691 --> 02:10:35,272
So we have 292 private ways.

1314
02:10:35,792 --> 02:10:38,694
Now most people will say, ha ha, I live on a private way.

1315
02:10:39,354 --> 02:10:39,835
Guess what?

1316
02:10:40,355 --> 02:10:44,977
There's no living on a private way.

1317
02:10:45,398 --> 02:10:49,960
It might be because in certain circumstances, you may have to pay for it.

1318
02:10:50,925 --> 02:10:53,748
You may have to pay to have a tree limb taken down.

1319
02:10:54,008 --> 02:10:57,791
You may have to pay to have a sidewalk done because you're on a private way.

1320
02:10:59,273 --> 02:11:06,780
Um, the rest of the roads, uh, and that's 60 a city streets.

1321
02:11:07,540 --> 02:11:15,688
So I took a look at the numbers over the last four and a half, close to five years to try to get a picture on how many streets we doing per year.

1322
02:11:16,663 --> 02:11:18,846
And how much money are we getting from the state?

1323
02:11:19,226 --> 02:11:23,251
And at what point are we going to be able to complete our streets?

1324
02:11:23,271 --> 02:11:25,533
You know, we hear about complete streets all the time.

1325
02:11:26,014 --> 02:11:28,977
That's the biggest misnomer ever, complete streets.

1326
02:11:29,458 --> 02:11:29,698
We get 500,000.

1327
02:11:29,878 --> 02:11:33,522
We do a few small projects and we call it complete streets.

1328
02:11:34,403 --> 02:11:35,685
I don't know what they're completed, but.

1329
02:11:36,512 --> 02:11:37,292
That's what we call it.

1330
02:11:37,332 --> 02:11:46,596
So over the past four and a half years, we've paved altogether 30 streets in the city over four and a half years.

1331
02:11:46,896 --> 02:11:48,376
I like to round it off to five years.

1332
02:11:49,256 --> 02:11:56,759
Out of the 30 streets, nine were full streets where we ground the street down and repaved it.

1333
02:11:57,219 --> 02:12:00,080
So we did nine full streets in almost five years.

1334
02:12:00,720 --> 02:12:03,201
And the other 21 streets were partial.

1335
02:12:03,661 --> 02:12:05,002
They went up 500 yards on a road.

1336
02:12:06,295 --> 02:12:10,459
or they went from one intersection to the first intersection of the street.

1337
02:12:10,760 --> 02:12:11,941
So they weren't full streets.

1338
02:12:12,501 --> 02:12:18,848
But for my point, Mr. President, rather than trying to figure this out, I'm going to go based on the 30 streets.

1339
02:12:19,268 --> 02:12:22,511
So this city does 30 streets every five years.

1340
02:12:23,452 --> 02:12:24,033
So that's what?

1341
02:12:24,193 --> 02:12:26,735
Six streets a year, if you average it out.

1342
02:12:27,596 --> 02:12:29,698
A street grind and repave.

1343
02:12:30,508 --> 02:12:32,929
which we heard tonight in Committee of the Whole meeting.

1344
02:12:34,169 --> 02:12:51,016
The repaving is not lost, used to 2025, and that could be for increased traffic on a, trucking on a street, and pulling off the tie, which we heard from DPW tonight.

1345
02:12:51,696 --> 02:12:55,337
But a typical grind and pave, 15 times,

1346
02:12:58,422 --> 02:13:14,447
So if you take this and logically go through it, if we continue to pave the streets every five years, after 20 years, we will have of the 438 streets.

1347
02:13:14,467 --> 02:13:20,548
At that point of after five years, and then after 20 years,

1348
02:13:35,828 --> 02:13:37,449
We'll be working on 15 to 20.

1349
02:13:41,552 --> 02:13:46,716
This address any of the private roads I'm talking about.

1350
02:13:47,236 --> 02:13:56,103
So when you add in the other 300 roads, the figures that I'm coming up with are strictly only going based off the streets that I considered private, which is 438.

1351
02:13:59,088 --> 02:14:12,656
According to get out, Mr. President, we will never, ever in the way we're spending allocating money on our streets, we will never, ever get ahead on repaving our roads.

1352
02:14:13,157 --> 02:14:14,617
We are always going to be catching up.

1353
02:14:14,998 --> 02:14:17,899
We are always going to be doing our streets piecemeal.

1354
02:14:18,780 --> 02:14:26,825
I asked the city engineer's office, can you provide me with a list, a working list of the next priority of streets?

1355
02:14:28,059 --> 02:14:28,980
I could not get one.

1356
02:14:29,580 --> 02:14:40,310
I could get a list of the 30 streets that were done over the past four and a half years, but I couldn't get a street listing of what the next priorities are.

1357
02:14:40,730 --> 02:14:50,058
And I think that's some of the frustration with feeling behind this reel when residents come up and say, you know, my street hasn't been looked at in six decades.

1358
02:14:51,219 --> 02:14:52,120
Six decades.

1359
02:14:53,341 --> 02:14:55,483
So, Mr. President, it's clear to me

1360
02:14:56,604 --> 02:15:16,250
In order to get ahead of the curve, we as a city can take advantage of the Chapter 90 money and the reimbursement, but we also have to put money, allocate money in our budget every year in DPW or engineering, specifically for road repavement, Mr. President.

1361
02:15:17,471 --> 02:15:21,512
And if we allocate an additional million dollars in that year,

1362
02:15:22,863 --> 02:15:31,951
We go up from 28% of the streets that are being done in five years to 52% or 54%, whatever the math comes out to.

1363
02:15:33,433 --> 02:15:38,678
It has that much of an impact, adding another million dollars a year to our roads.

1364
02:15:40,304 --> 02:15:54,797
So, you know, knowing it's the top, in my opinion, one of the top three priorities in this community, knowing that we're never going to get ahead from previous experience on the money we're receiving, that we need to do this, Mr. President.

1365
02:15:55,198 --> 02:16:03,185
We as a council, during this year's budget, I'm sure other councils have other priorities, traffic engineer and a lot of other issues out there.

1366
02:16:03,568 --> 02:16:18,144
But we as a council have to stand up as a body and say, you know what, based on the complaints we get, based on the poor condition of our streets, based on a number of issues, Madam Mayor, we need you to add an additional $1 million

1367
02:16:19,770 --> 02:16:20,931
$2 million would be even better.

1368
02:16:21,151 --> 02:16:23,253
That'd be 75% of our roads.

1369
02:16:23,274 --> 02:16:33,143
$3 million would be a panacea and bring us to a target level of completing all our streets after a certain number of years.

1370
02:16:34,124 --> 02:16:39,809
That may not be realistic, Mr. President, but I think at least putting an additional million dollars.

1371
02:16:40,710 --> 02:16:48,917
Now we can all talk a big game when the residents come up, and we can sympathize, and we can cry crocodile tears when they come up and say, oh my God, that's awful.

1372
02:16:49,538 --> 02:16:52,661
But we have to do something as a council, Mr. President.

1373
02:16:52,921 --> 02:16:55,443
We have to stand up and take action.

1374
02:16:56,424 --> 02:16:57,905
And this is the only way it's gonna happen.

1375
02:16:58,126 --> 02:17:02,529
Have you ever heard anyone from the city administration step up and say, we need more money for the roads?

1376
02:17:03,590 --> 02:17:05,112
Absolutely not, Mr. President.

1377
02:17:06,090 --> 02:17:19,838
I've been on this council 16 years, Mr. President, and I've never heard one person from DPW, engineering, or the city administration ever step up and say, you know what, based on the poor condition of our roads, we need some additional funding.

1378
02:17:22,720 --> 02:17:30,405
I received a number of pitches via email because this was on the agenda and the street

1379
02:17:35,456 --> 02:17:36,057
that are sinking.

1380
02:17:36,357 --> 02:17:43,184
By the way, the Chapter 9 money is used not just to repave, it's used for infrastructure improvements.

1381
02:17:43,744 --> 02:17:49,189
So if you have a catch basin that's sinking, that money can be used to rebuild the catch basin.

1382
02:17:50,370 --> 02:17:56,897
If you have a manhole cover that's sinking or has potholes all around it, that could be used to fix the manhole cover.

1383
02:17:57,525 --> 02:18:03,870
You have curbing that's level with the street now, like Riverside Ave, that I've been complaining about, Mr. President.

1384
02:18:04,691 --> 02:18:07,954
When you drive down Riverside Ave, the curbing is level with the road.

1385
02:18:08,874 --> 02:18:09,935
How unsafe is that?

1386
02:18:12,097 --> 02:18:17,902
So these are the infrastructure improvements, Mr. President, along with sidewalks as well, that can be done with this money.

1387
02:18:18,763 --> 02:18:21,285
And in my opinion, it's long overdue.

1388
02:18:21,645 --> 02:18:25,028
It's a top issue in this community, public safety and roads.

1389
02:18:25,772 --> 02:18:30,914
And, uh, we need to address it, Mr. President, just to give people an idea what it costs.

1390
02:18:31,634 --> 02:18:37,216
Um, Stearns Ave in South Method had their road repaved not too long ago.

1391
02:18:38,176 --> 02:18:39,857
Um, I think it was back in 2013.

1392
02:18:41,737 --> 02:18:43,118
It was a few years back.

1393
02:18:43,878 --> 02:18:49,100
And that street, which probably has maybe 12 homes the length of the street,

1394
02:18:49,453 --> 02:18:56,996
maybe 13, cost the city $85,000 for full grind and a repave.

1395
02:18:58,256 --> 02:19:08,920
So I think it puts it in perspective, knowing the size of that street and comparing it to other streets that, you know, we can get through a lot of streets if we put the money towards it.

1396
02:19:09,540 --> 02:19:15,682
We can accomplish our goals if we're able, Mr. President, to make this a priority, which it should be.

1397
02:19:17,040 --> 02:19:20,362
You shouldn't have to use radar when you're running down the streets.

1398
02:19:21,703 --> 02:19:23,905
I come down the streets, I know exactly where the potholes are.

1399
02:19:24,165 --> 02:19:26,527
I go like that, I drive, I know exactly where they are.

1400
02:19:26,847 --> 02:19:32,071
I know where the manhole covers are too low, I know where all the bumps are, and it's a shame, Mr. President.

1401
02:19:32,371 --> 02:19:38,555
That shows you how long that our roads have been inflicted with these ripples and potholes.

1402
02:19:39,336 --> 02:19:43,779
So I would respectfully ask my colleagues, Mr. President, on a vote tonight,

1403
02:19:44,350 --> 02:19:55,142
To ask the mayor, I know we just received some of our budget and we got our budget book and we're going to start meeting with department heads, that this is in the early stages of the budget.

1404
02:19:55,422 --> 02:20:00,488
We haven't sat down at all yet that a million dollars be appropriated, Mr. President.

1405
02:20:00,908 --> 02:20:10,836
towards the repaving of our roads and that we also have a systematic approach on priorities of roads that need to be repaired.

1406
02:20:11,277 --> 02:20:16,301
So we don't have to go to the engineering office and say, well, we really don't have a list.

1407
02:20:16,941 --> 02:20:19,623
It's done by calls that we receive.

1408
02:20:19,643 --> 02:20:21,345
Then we go out and look at them.

1409
02:20:21,405 --> 02:20:25,288
And then if the mayor wants to do them, we get them done.

1410
02:20:26,730 --> 02:20:28,832
You know, there's really no list, Mr. President.

1411
02:20:29,093 --> 02:20:40,228
There should be a list on the city website that any resident can go there and see if they're on the priority list, see where their street falls, and expect the date that their street may be done, Mr. President.

1412
02:20:40,909 --> 02:20:42,131
This is not rocket science.

1413
02:20:43,743 --> 02:20:51,888
And again, as I preference my remarks all the time, this is no reflection on a depleted DPW department.

1414
02:20:52,548 --> 02:20:56,091
It's no reflection on the good work that they do, Mr. President.

1415
02:20:56,511 --> 02:21:08,298
But clearly, you know, from past experience and from past knowledge that we're going nowhere, how we're currently operating with repaving our streets.

1416
02:21:08,618 --> 02:21:11,520
And I offer this, Mr. President, as a way to

1417
02:21:12,781 --> 02:21:25,629
have an approach that can address one of the top concerns from residents that contact me, phone me, email me, stop me at stop and shop or wherever else I am about the condition of our roads.

1418
02:21:25,989 --> 02:21:38,078
So I would ask that in a formal vote tonight, Mr. President, that we request the mayor put an additional million dollars in the paving budget for either DPW or engineering.

1419
02:21:38,918 --> 02:21:39,859
Thank you, Mr. Vice President.

1420
02:21:41,930 --> 02:22:06,132
Mr. President, several months ago this council voted on a resolution that I sponsored requesting that the DPW perform a complete assessment of our streets and the resolution requested that they consider adopting new technology and right now there is an opportunity for the City of Medford to utilize infrared technology and it pretty much is a truck that drives down the street and takes an x-ray of the road and uses infrared technology to determine

1421
02:22:07,107 --> 02:22:11,788
the quality of the infrastructure below the ground, as well as the defects of the infrastructure above the ground, Mr. President.

1422
02:22:12,948 --> 02:22:15,629
I've had the opportunity to take a look at one of these machines.

1423
02:22:15,649 --> 02:22:23,430
A local business on Mystic Avenue, Millennium Power Sweeping, is in possession of one, and this tool can work miracles.

1424
02:22:24,050 --> 02:22:32,112
It can repair potholes and do a whole entire assessment of the roadway all in one felt swoop, Mr. President.

1425
02:22:33,183 --> 02:22:35,644
I certainly think that this is a noble resolution.

1426
02:22:37,325 --> 02:22:39,566
I don't know if a million bucks is going to be enough, Mr. President.

1427
02:22:40,246 --> 02:22:41,107
I don't think not.

1428
02:22:41,407 --> 02:22:45,469
If we're going to be putting out a budget, we're looking to add $1 million to it.

1429
02:22:45,489 --> 02:22:46,829
This budget is funded by ________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

1430
02:23:06,094 --> 02:23:25,203
However, I would like to include in this resolution an amendment asking that, number one, the infrared technology be utilized, and number two, I think that it's important that the public be informed.

1431
02:23:26,442 --> 02:23:29,103
maybe do a trial run with the truck?

1432
02:23:29,763 --> 02:23:32,304
I do believe that they've done that already, Mr. President.

1433
02:23:32,444 --> 02:23:44,287
And I think that Melanie might have been utilized to do a test run, performing repairs to some cracks on some basketball courts to show how far along technology's come.

1434
02:23:45,227 --> 02:23:49,708
So I certainly don't have a problem asking for a complete assessment.

1435
02:23:49,768 --> 02:23:53,849
I think it's premature to request funding until we get the assessment done, because we really don't know what it's going to cost.

1436
02:23:53,909 --> 02:23:55,810
I think Councillor Marks has done a great job putting this

1437
02:23:56,383 --> 02:24:01,776
I would like an opportunity to review the numbers a little further.

1438
02:24:02,257 --> 02:24:05,846
I did get a response from the administration that it would cost about $7 million to

1439
02:24:06,663 --> 02:24:09,144
We can pave our emergency arteries in their entirety.

1440
02:24:09,604 --> 02:24:15,147
And the question comes is whether or not we can use tax agent money to do that or if there are other funding sources that are available to us as well.

1441
02:24:15,207 --> 02:24:23,331
So I certainly can appreciate the resolution, however, for us right now to add a million dollars to the proposed budget I think is premature.

1442
02:24:23,371 --> 02:24:27,173
I think we should start a budget discussions and deliberations and find out where money's going.

1443
02:24:28,493 --> 02:24:30,795
Based on last year's fiscal year budget, I think we have close to 605.

1444
02:24:32,266 --> 02:24:43,213
$100,000 of money that's used for contracted services, for services that could be performed in-house that's being performed out-house, for services that could go towards paying for salaries to replete the DPW staff.

1445
02:24:43,233 --> 02:24:48,556
So there's a number of items that we need to look at, Mr. President, and this is a priority, but there are other priorities as well, as the Councillor noted.

1446
02:24:49,236 --> 02:24:52,318
So I can certainly stand behind the resolution to ask for the assessment.

1447
02:24:53,099 --> 02:24:59,042
However, at this point in time, I'd feel very uncomfortable requesting that $1 million be added to the budget without further discussion to liberation and investigation.

